  "prompt": "How did Donald Trump win the electoral college but not the popular vote?",
  "response": "In the 2016 U.S. presidential election, Donald Trump won the Electoral College by securing 304 electoral votes, while Hillary Clinton won the popular vote by receiving approximately 2.9 million more individual votes nationwide. This occurred due to the way the Electoral College system works:\n\n1. Each state is allocated a number of electoral votes based on its total number of representatives in Congress.\n\n2. Most states use a \"winner-take-all\" system, where the candidate who wins the popular vote in that state receives all of its electoral votes.\n\n3. Trump won several key swing states by narrow margins, such as Wisconsin, Michigan, and Pennsylvania, which gave him enough electoral votes to win the presidency.\n\n4. Clinton's popular vote margin came largely from high-population states like California and New York, which she won by large margins.\n\nThe Electoral College system means that a candidate can win the presidency without winning the most individual votes nationwide, which has happened a few times in U.S. history, including in 2000 and 2016.",
